questiontext.text:
Exercise

    This exercise refers to the content covered in the previous sub-section.

  1. Compare the function \(h=35-4.9t^{2}\) with \(y=ax^{2}=bx+c\). The coefficient corresponding to \(a\) is [[1]], the coefficient corresponding to \(b\) is [[2]], and the coefficient corresponding to \(c\) is [[3]]. Given the value of \(a\) the parabola opens [[5]].

  2. An appropriate function for the variation of \(h\) with \(t\) if height is measured upwards from the top of a \(2\) m vehicle is \(h=\)[[6]]-[[9]]\(t^{2}\) for \(0\leq t\leq 2.5951\).

  3. Figure [[13]] represents a sketch of the function in question
    Figure A Figure B
       
     Figure C

generalfeedback.text:
1. There is no term that is linear in \(t\) therefore \(b=0\). The constant term is \(c\) therefore \(c=35\). Matching the quadratic coefficients gives \(a=-4.9\). 

  2. The solution is \(h=35-2-4.9t^{2}=33-4.9t^{2}\). The range for \(t\) cannot exceed \(t=2.5951\) since this is the time when the rock hits the ground.

  3. The answer is Figure B. It cannot be Figure A since this function is increasing and it cannot be Figure C since, for certain values of \(t\), \(s\) is negative.
